In [308]:
# Define Forward Propagation function
def forward_prop(w1, w2, x):
    z1 = np.dot(w1, x)
    a1 = sigmoid(z1)    
    z2 = np.dot(w2, a1)
    a2 = sigmoid(z2)
    return z1, a1, z2, a2

# Define Backward Propagation function
def back_prop(m, w1, w2, z1, a1, z2, a2, y):
    
    dz2 = a2-y
    dw2 = np.dot(dz2, a1.T)/m
    dz1 = np.dot(w2.T, dz2) * a1*(1-a1)
    dw1 = np.dot(dz1, total_input.T)/m
    dw1 = np.reshape(dw1, w1.shape)
    
    dw2 = np.reshape(dw2,w2.shape)    
    return dz2,dw2,dz1,dw1

# Train

losses = []
iterations = 10000

for i in range(iterations):
    z1, a1, z2, a2 = forward_prop(w1, w2, total_input)
    loss = -(1/samples)*np.sum(y*np.log(a2)+(1-y)*np.log(1-a2))
    losses.append(loss)
    da2, dw2, dz1, dw1 = back_prop(samples, w1, w2, z1, a1, z2, a2, y)
    w2 = w2-lr*dw2
    w1 = w1-lr*dw1

# We plot losses to see how our network is doing
plt.plot(losses)
plt.xlabel("EPOCHS")
plt.ylabel("Loss value")

# Build the base modelwith 8 neurons
model = keras.Sequential([
    keras.layers.Dense(8, activation='relu', input_dim=X_train.shape[1]),
    keras.layers.Dense(1, activation='sigmoid') # Use sigmoid for binary classification
])

# Compile the model
model.compile(optimizer=opt, 
              loss=loss_function, 
              metrics=['accuracy'])

# Define the early stopping callback
early_stopping = tf.keras.callbacks.EarlyStopping(
    monitor='val_loss',  # Metric to monitor for improvement
    patience=10,  # Number of epochs with no improvement after which training will be stopped
    restore_best_weights=True  # Restore the weights of the best epoch
)

with tf.device('/device:GPU:0'):
    # Train the model on GPU
    model.fit(X_train, 
              y_train, 
              epochs=epoch_size, 
              batch_size=24, 
              validation_data=(X_val, y_val), 
              callbacks=[early_stopping]) 

# save loss history
model_hist = model.history.history['loss']

# Evaluate the model

print('Test loss:', loss)

Part ii: Add More Hidden Layers + Batch Normalization¶

In [73]:
# Build the model
model_more_hidden_batch = keras.Sequential([
    keras.layers.Dense(64, activation='relu'),
    keras.layers.Dense(64, activation='relu'),
    keras.layers.BatchNormalization(), # Batch Normalization
    keras.layers.Dense(64, activation='relu'),
    keras.layers.Dense(64, activation='relu'),
    keras.layers.BatchNormalization(), # Batch Normalization
    keras.layers.Dense(64, activation='relu'),
    keras.layers.Dense(64, activation='relu'),
    keras.layers.Dense(1, activation='sigmoid')
])

# Compile the model
model_more_hidden_batch.compile(optimizer=opt, 
               loss=loss_function, 
               metrics=['accuracy'])

# Create a TensorBoard callback
tensorboard_callback = tf.keras.callbacks.TensorBoard(log_dir='./logs', histogram_freq=1)

# Define the early stopping callback
early_stopping = tf.keras.callbacks.EarlyStopping(
    monitor='val_loss',  # Metric to monitor for improvement
    patience=10,  # Number of epochs with no improvement after which training will be stopped
    restore_best_weights=True  # Restore the weights of the best epoch
)

# Train the model
with tf.device('/device:GPU:0'):
    model_more_hidden_batch.fit(X_train,
                      y_train, 
                      epochs=epoch_size, 
                      batch_size=16,
                      validation_data=(X_val, y_val), 
                      callbacks=[tensorboard_callback, early_stopping]) 

# save loss history
model_more_hidden_batch_hist = model_more_hidden_batch.history.history['loss']

# Evaluate the model
loss_hidden, accuracy_hidden = model_more_hidden_batch.evaluate(X_test, y_test)
print('Test loss:', loss_hidden)
print('Test accuracy:', accuracy_hidden)

# Build the model
model_reg_drop = keras.Sequential([
    keras.layers.Dense(64, activation='relu'),
    keras.layers.Dense(64, activation='relu', kernel_regularizer=regularizers.l2(0.05)), # Regularization
    keras.layers.BatchNormalization(), # Batch Normalization

Part C¶

Explain how adding various hyperparameters may have impacted model performance.

  • Hidden Layers: Adding more hidden layers alone does not improved the Test accuracy from 65%. It goes to 52%.
  • Batch Normalization: Adding more hidden layers AND batch normalization improves the Test accuracy from 65% to 71%.
  • Regularization: Adding L2 Regularization on top of the model slightly improves the Test accuracy from 71% to 73%.
  • Dropout: Adding a dropout of 25% to help generalization brought the final Test accuracy to 71%. This is OK because additional validation on unseen data should be stronger with this dropout.

Overall the base model Test Accuracy was 70% and the final model with extra hidden layers, batch norm, regularization, and dropout had a Test Accuracy of 71%.

Loss Plot Summary:

  • This loss plot comparison between the final model and base model shows the additional hyperparameters improved loss overall. At the beginning the final model has a much lower loss but the base model quickly catches up around 5 epochs. Both level off after 5-10 epochs suggesting we can stop the training at this point.

Part D¶

Summarize the model architecture and provide a manual calculation for the total number of parameters used in your neural network and check your results with Keras summary.

Summary: The final model had a total of 10 layers, including the final sigmoid layer that performs the classification to 0 or 1. Aside from the last sigmoid layer, all other layers used ReLu activations. There are also 2 BatchNormalization layers, a 25% dropout layer, and 2 layers that include L2 regularization.

Parameters: 21,953 Total

m = input n = output

  • Layer 1: (m+1)n = (8+1)64 = 576
  • Layer 2: (m+1)n = (64+1)64 = 4,160
  • Layer 3: BatchNorm = (m+m)n = (64+64)2 = 256
  • Layer 4: (m+1)n = (64+1)64 = 4,160
  • Layer 5: (m+1)n = (64+1)64 = 4,160
  • Layer 6: BatchNorm = (m+m)n = (64+64)2 = 256
  • Layer 7: (m+1)n = (64+1)64 = 4,160
  • Layer 8: Dropout = 0
  • Layer 9: (m+1)n = (64+1)64 = 4,160
  • Layer 10: (m+n) = (64+1) = 65

Sum = 576 + 4160 + 256 + 4160 + 4160 + 256 + 4160 + 0 + 4160 + 65 = 21,953

Part E - Summary¶

Comparing our deep learning model against 2 classical ML models showed the following Test accuracy results:

  • Deep Learning: 70.78%
  • Logistic Regression: 76%
  • SVM: 77%

This means that simpler models can perform just as well as a more complicated neural net model with the diabetes dataset. Even though the deep learning model achieves a strong accuracy, the much simpler logistic regression and SVM models outperforms it. For this reason, I would suggest starting with classical machine learning models first before implementing a deep learning solution as they are quicker and more efficient to implement.

Sigmoid Function¶

In [128]:
X = np.random.uniform(-10, 10, size=5000)
y = 1 / (1 + np.exp(-X))
In [129]:
# Build the Keras model
model = keras.Sequential([
    layers.Dense(16, activation='sigmoid', input_shape=(1,)),
    layers.Dense(16, activation='sigmoid'),
    layers.Dense(1)
])

# Compile the model
model.compile(optimizer='adam', 
              loss='mean_squared_error')

with tf.device('/device:GPU:0'):
    model.fit(X, y, epochs=20, batch_size=32)

In [124]:
X = np.linspace(-np.pi, np.pi, 10000)
y = 1 / (1 + np.exp(-X))

predictions = model.predict(X) 

# Create the plot
plt.plot(X, y, label='Sigmoid Function') # true sigmoid function
plt.plot(X, predictions, label='Learned Sigmoid Function') # modeled sigmoid function

# Set the plot title and labels
plt.title('Sigmoid Function')
plt.xlabel('x')
plt.ylabel('Sigmoid(x)')

# Display the plot
plt.legend()
plt.show()

Architecture Summary¶

The model used to learn the sigmoid function has 3 total layers. The first 2 layers have 16 neurons (units) and sigmoid activation functions. The input accepts a 1 dimensional input. The last layer is a fully connected layer with a single neuron. The model has a total of 321 parameters.
